text: hi everyone anthony fantano here the
internet's busiest music nerd and it's
time for a review of the new delete zeke
album frailty this is the second project
to drop this year from producer
multi-instrumentalist songwriter and
singer delete zeke which isn't the only
pseudonym this artist records under but
it is certainly now the most popular one
they do a change which occurred in a
relatively short amount of time as a lot
of the earliest official delete zeke
singles date back to around the time the
pandemic lockdowns began which
eventually led to
earlier this year and now frailty just
months later where we get a really
curious and dizzying array of genres
mashed together pretty aggressively
think like porter robinson and emo
adjacent pop punk but then all of that
filtered through bits of bedroom pop
glitch pop noise pop hyper pop various
strains of electronic music alt and
grunge rock too all that culminating
into 13 tracks that don't just blur
genre lines but also build up into these
grand multi-faceted anthems so i don't
mean this as a dig but it doesn't
exactly sound like frailty had a huge
you know budget behind its production or
anything but nevertheless zeke's
compositions as well as sound palettes
on these tracks are consistently
creative and impressive there's just
loads of imagination packed into every
corner of this lp case and point on a
few tracks like eyes off the wheel i'm a
star which undergoes so many radical
aesthetic changes along its run time
zeke might have accidentally invented a
few genres in the process there's also
the song misplaced which begins as a
very murky piece of lo-fi rock
eventually shifting into this really
chipper electro with an 8-bit edge then
escalating into this intense wall of
zippy synthesizers fuzzy distortions as
well as grand midi horns it feels like
i'm listening to the glow part too but
for terminally online zoomers then
there's the even longer movies for guys
which begins with this pumping sort of
alternative electro sort of reminds me
of the early work of acts like crystal
castles the track eventually moves into
these mystical and fuzzy layers of
synthesizers then of course a bunch of
confusing dizzying electronics noise
rock passages as you do finishing things
off with a very somber outro with some
milky bass lines and deadpan but
sad vocal leads then keep in mind again
this is all happening within one track i
really feel like i'm dimension hopping
as i'm moving from section to section of
these songs i have to give kudos on the
sequencing of the lp as well the songs
along the
track list here really play off of each
other's energy really well namely cuts
like your clothes for example which is a
great throttling exciting moment right
after the intro track love the crunchy
lo-fi guitar riffs and impassioned
choruses on this one i also appreciate
how certain tracks on the lp segue into
each other too misplace and a pretender
how to lie and to champ as well as the
closing tracks so frailty is nothing if
not a cohesive listen and at a very
early stage in delete zeke's discography
it's been shown that
zeke has a real way with songwriting
especially when being able to i guess
launch off into these
various compositional and aesthetic
detours but still at the end of it
making it all sound really cohesive and
focused which now brings me to the
achilles heel of the record and it is a
big one because of how major of a focus
it is and that's the singing which isn't
awful i think on a handful of tracks or
just kind of sampling one here and there
it's listenable it's tolerable but as i
finished frailty and listened to it
again and again and again it just became
apparent that the vocals the singing has
a very limited range a very relaxed tone
and nasal timbre as well it's like i'm
listening to an emo asmr video and the
robotic manipulations on delete zeke's
vocals are pretty much present on every
single track here which i think prevents
the vocals from having a more intimate
impact during the more stripped back
spots on the project can you tell buzz
daisy as well as the intro track the
vocals just showcase so little variation
it makes the whole lp feel more one note
than it actually is and finally while i
think for a majority of this lp zeke
does a lot of great things within a
super confined and lo-fi space there are
moments where these limitations i think
kneecap some of the records more grand
instrumental ambitions like on the
closing track where uh some of the
crescendos there i feel like are just
being crushed under uh the weight and
the limitations uh that they're
presented with in terms of like volume
and space so yes i think on frailty
there's a lot of great tracks there's a
lot of great ideas a lot of great sounds
and concepts but in the future i would
love to see more of that applied to the
vocals and hopefully like
zeke's visions can be applied to a
better recording and mix as well to
really make some of these amazing ideas
